<subSubSection id="EF99455F23D9FADB90CEAF185BA6B9B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="BE75E757E9CD956E5862118F86FAB1DC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86FD5FC509000101CECDEEEDD324EAAF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This is the Hispaniola counterpart of 
<taxonomicName id="5096410D3E9A87CD156666E2940C291F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lineolata">
<emphasis id="52CBDD4BB3F1BAC0216BAB61E7C3AAEC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea lineolata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B0502CCD320E50A8E337E6923C7CCB87" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="carolina">
<emphasis id="CB3ED87960FB36055178F1AEE3AAB8F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. carolina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is distinguished by its relatively long, usually oblanceolate leaflets and the relatively long peduncles and pedicels.
</paragraph>
